The '''Sydney Metro''' is an [[Automatic train operation|automated]] [[rapid transit]] system in [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. It currently consists of one route, the [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line]], running between [[Tallawong railway station|Tallawong]] and [[Sydenham railway station, Sydney|Sydenham]] and consisting of 21 stations on {{convert|52|km|mi|abbr=on}} of twin tracks, mostly underground. 

The first line of the network, between [[Tallawong, New South Wales|Tallawong]] and [[Chatswood, New South Wales|Chatswood]], was initially opened in May 2019 and has since been extended from Chatswood to [[Sydenham railway station, Sydney|Sydenham]] as of August 2024, as part of the first stage of the [[Sydney Metro City & Southwest|City & Southwest]] project.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news |last=Gerathy |first=Sarah |date=19 August 2024 |title=The Sydney Metro City line is finally open. Here's what you need to know |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-08-19/sydney-metro-city-line-opening-explainer/104166354 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240818192607/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-08-19/sydney-metro-city-line-opening-explainer/104166354 |archive-date=18 August 2024 |access-date=19 August 2024 |work=ABC News}}</ref> The second stage of the project will then further extend this line to Bankstown as part of a partial conversion of the existing [[Bankstown railway line]] with a scheduled completion in mid-to-late 2026.<ref name="2026-completion">{{cite web |title=South West Metro conversion period to be extended into 2026 {{!}} NSW Government |url=https://www.nsw.gov.au/ministerial-releases/south-west-metro-conversion-period-to-be-extended-into-2026 |publisher=NSW Government |language=en-AU |date=5 March 2025}}</ref>

Two additional lines are also under construction, as part of the [[Sydney Metro West]] and [[Sydney Metro Western Sydney Airport|Western Sydney Airport]] projects. The Western Sydney Airport project will construct a line approximately {{Convert|23|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[St Marys, New South Wales|St Marys]] to the new [[Bradfield railway station, Sydney|Bradfield Station]] in [[Badgerys Creek]]. It will comprise six stations and service the [[Western Sydney Airport|Western Sydney International (Nancy-Bird Walton) Airport]], which is also currently under construction, upon its opening in 2026.

Sydney Metro West will construct a {{Convert|24|km|mi|abbr=on}} new line from [[Westmead, New South Wales|Westmead]] to [[Hunter Street railway station|a new station at Hunter Street]] in the Sydney CBD. It will comprise ten stations, serviced by fully underground twin tracks. The line will service [[Parramatta]] and [[Sydney Olympic Park]] upon opening in 2032.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/metro-west-to-supercharge-housing-supply | title=Metro West to supercharge housing supply across Sydney &#124; NSW Government | date=7 December 2023 | access-date=18 February 2024 | archive-date=8 March 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240308093617/https://www.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/metro-west-to-supercharge-housing-supply | url-status=live }}</ref>

When all current projects are complete, the network will amount to a total of 46 stations and {{Convert|113|km|mi|abbr=on}} of track.

The [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line]] of the Sydney Metro is Australia's only fully automated heavy rail system.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sydney's first metro line a revolution for Australian transport|url=https://www.railjournal.com/in_depth/sydneys-first-metro-line-australian-transport/|access-date=14 January 2021|website=International Railway Journal|language=en|archive-date=16 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116042653/https://www.railjournal.com/in_depth/sydneys-first-metro-line-australian-transport/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=29 May 2019|title=Australia's first metro system opened in Sydney|url=https://www.urban-transport-magazine.com/en/australias-first-metro-system-opened-in-sydney/|access-date=14 January 2021|website=Urban Transport Magazine|language=en-US|archive-date=16 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116000858/https://www.urban-transport-magazine.com/en/australias-first-metro-system-opened-in-sydney/|url-status=live}}</ref> It is managed by the Sydney Metro agency, under the umbrella of [[Transport for NSW]]. Services are operated by [[Metro Trains Sydney]] and integrated with the established [[Sydney Trains]] network. Its {{convert|52|km|mi|abbr=on}} line also makes it the third-longest single driverless rapid transit line in the world, behind [[Rapid KL]] [[Putrajaya line]] and the [[Red Line (Dubai Metro)|Dubai Metro Red Line]].

==History==
===Earlier proposals===
{{main|Sydney Metro (2008 proposal)}}

The first proposals for a metro system in Sydney were put forward in 2001, when Co-ordinator-General of Rail [[Ron Christie (rail administrator)|Ron Christie]] released his "Long-term Strategic Plan for Rail" report, outlining long-term goals for the expansion of the rail network.<ref>{{cite report |last=Ron |first=Christie |title=Long-Term Strategic Plan for Rail |date=June 2001 |chapter=1. Introduction |chapter-url=http://www.aptnsw.org.au/christie/ |access-date=15 June 2015 |archive-date=17 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217135059/http://www.aptnsw.org.au/christie/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He suggested that some "metro" lines—operationally independent from the [[Sydney Trains|existing network]]—should be constructed past 2020 due to capacity constraints.<ref>{{cite report |last=Ron |first=Christie |title=Long-Term Strategic Plan for Rail |date=June 2001 |chapter=5. Beyond 2010: Overcoming the critical inner city constraint and implementing a longer term vision |chapter-url=http://www.aptnsw.org.au/christie/ |access-date=15 June 2015 |archive-date=17 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217135059/http://www.aptnsw.org.au/christie/ |url-status=live }}</ref> This was later dismissed by the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]] as only a "shopping list" of potential projects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christie Report|url=http://www.aptnsw.org.au/christie/|website=Action for Public Transport|access-date=14 June 2015|archive-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217135059/http://www.aptnsw.org.au/christie/|url-status=live}}</ref>

The idea for a metro resurfaced in late 2007 when discussions about an underground 'Anzac Line' took place within the NSW Government. The line would have run from [[West Ryde, New South Wales|West Ryde]] in Sydney's northwest to [[Malabar, New South Wales|Malabar]] in the southeast but did not come to fruition.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Besser|first1=Linton|author1-link=Linton Besser|title=New east-west line may cut congestion|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/new-sydney-tunnel-proposal/2007/09/13/1189276899575.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1|website=Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|access-date=14 June 2015|date=14 September 2007|archive-date=18 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240818222425/https://www.smh.com.au/national/new-east-west-line-may-cut-congestion-20070914-gdr3u8.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catalyst.com.au/Public_files/Long-Term_Strategic_Plan_for_Rail_Overview_13_June_2001.pdf|title=Long Term Strategic Plan for Rail|work=catalyst.com.au|date=June 2001|access-date=13 June 2015|archive-date=30 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730140557/http://www.catalyst.com.au/Public_files/Long-Term_Strategic_Plan_for_Rail_Overview_13_June_2001.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> In early 2008, following the shelving of various heavy rail expansion projects from the 2005 [[Proposed railways in Sydney#Metropolitan Rail Expansion Program, 2005|Metropolitan Rail Expansion Program]] (MREP), the Government officially announced the {{convert|37|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Sydney Metro (2008 proposal)|North West Metro]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Besser|first1=Linton|author1-link=Linton Besser|title=Bye heavy rail, now for a north-west metro|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/bye-heavy-rail-now-for-a-northwest-metro/2008/02/25/1203788248514.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1|website=Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|access-date=14 June 2015|date=26 February 2008|archive-date=18 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240818222300/https://widgets.outbrain.com/nanoWidget/externals/topics/topics.html?r=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.smh.com.au#contentSwap1|url-status=live}}</ref> Expected to cost $12 billion, it would have linked [[Rouse Hill]] in Sydney's northwest with the [[Sydney central business district|CBD]], with construction starting in 2010 and finishing in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iemma|first1=Morris|title=Premier Iemma unveils Sydney's first Euro-style metro rail project|url=http://www.nsw.gov.au/docs/080318_Transport_SydneyLink.pdf|publisher=NSW Government|access-date=14 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720202842/http://www.nsw.gov.au/docs/080318_Transport_SydneyLink.pdf|archive-date=20 July 2008}}</ref>

The construction of the North West Metro was dependent upon the privatisation of the electricity network,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gittins|first1=Ross|title=Iemma's reasons for privatising electricity|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/iemmas-reasons-for-privatising-electricity-20080316-1zsa.html|access-date=14 June 2015|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=17 March 2008|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924145451/http://www.smh.com.au/business/iemmas-reasons-for-privatising-electricity-20080316-1zsa.html|url-status=live}}</ref> but, after a change of the state's [[Premier of New South Wales|Premier]] in late 2008, it was cancelled due to budgetary concerns. Its replacement was the {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}}, $4 billion [[Sydney Metro (2008 proposal)#Stage 1: CBD Metro|CBD Metro]], a shortened route running from [[Rozelle]] in the inner-west and into the CBD through to [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central railway station]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Simon|title=Northwest Metro rail link officially shelved|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/northwest-metro-rail-disaster/story-e6freuzi-1111117906366|access-date=14 June 2015|date=31 October 2008|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Construction was scheduled to start in 2010, like its predecessor, but would finish earlier in 2015. The CBD Metro was to have formed the "central spine" of a future metro network, with a planned [[Sydney Metro (2008 proposal)#Stage 2: West Metro|West Metro]] extension to [[Westmead, New South Wales|Westmead]] and [[Parramatta]] to be constructed soon after, subject to Federal funding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metro: The future of Sydney's transport|url=http://www.sydneymetro.nsw.gov.au/news/latest_news/west_metro/files/338/Metro_Thefutureoftransport.pdf|publisher=NSW Government|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704030225/http://www.sydneymetro.nsw.gov.au/news/latest_news/west_metro/files/338/Metro_Thefutureoftransport.pdf|archive-date=4 July 2009|date=30 June 2009}}</ref>

Reception to the plans was mixed, with [[Leader of the Opposition (New South Wales)|Opposition leader]] [[Barry O'Farrell]] accusing the Premier of "making it up as he goes along" after costings were not released until after the press conference;<ref>{{cite news|title=Metro-sexual Rees flags new rail link|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/metro-sexual-rees-flags-new-rail-link/story-e6freuzi-1111117843701|date=24 October 2008|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> criticism came from the [[The Greens NSW|Greens]] because the route seemed designed to pass through marginal electoral seats.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Clennel, Andrew|author2=Besser, Linton|author2-link=Linton Besser|title=CBD Metro cost jumps $1.3b in six months|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/cbd-metro-cost-jumps-13b-in-six-months-20090420-acqa.html|access-date=14 June 2015|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=21 April 2009|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924183900/http://www.smh.com.au/national/cbd-metro-cost-jumps-13b-in-six-months-20090420-acqa.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The Government's initial submission to [[Infrastructure Australia]] for funding was rejected due to "a lack of integrated planning".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Alexandra|title='Inadequate' submission puts NSW down the list|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/inadequate-submission-puts-nsw-down-the-list/2009/02/05/1233423405333.html|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=6 February 2009|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924201935/http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/inadequate-submission-puts-nsw-down-the-list/2009/02/05/1233423405333.html|url-status=live}}</ref> It was later revealed that the cost had jumped from $4 billion to $5.3 billion in six months,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ralston|first1=Nick|title=Rees reveals new Sydney Metro plan|url=http://www.smh.com.au//national/rees-reveals-new-sydney-metro-plan-20081024-57x2.html|access-date=14 June 2015|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=24 October 2008|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924102929/http://www.smh.com.au//national/rees-reveals-new-sydney-metro-plan-20081024-57x2.html|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as that internal estimates showed that the metro would run at only 15% of its maximum capacity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Besser|first1=Linton|author1-link=Linton Besser|title=CBD Metro will run almost empty|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/cbd-metro-will-run-almost-empty-20090503-argd.html|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=4 May 2009|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924183903/http://www.smh.com.au/national/cbd-metro-will-run-almost-empty-20090503-argd.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

The CBD Metro was cancelled in early 2010 after the Premier was [[2009 New South Wales Labor Party leadership spill|deposed]] a few months before in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Keneally rolls Rees and takes top job|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-12-03/keneally-rolls-rees-and-takes-top-job/1168764|agency=AAP|publisher=ABC News|date=4 December 2009|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=3 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803211337/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-12-03/keneally-rolls-rees-and-takes-top-job/1168764|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Keneally scraps CBD Metro plans|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-02-21/keneally-scraps-cbd-metro-plans/338076|agency=ABC/AAP|publisher=ABC News|date=22 February 2010|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=22 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122013435/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-02-21/keneally-scraps-cbd-metro-plans/338076|url-status=live}}</ref> The Government had spent almost $410 million on the project.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haynes|first1=Rhys|title=Metro rail plan was 'wasteful'|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/metro-rail-plan-was-wasteful/story-e6freuzi-1225964809704|date=3 December 2010|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> The new Premier [[Kristina Keneally]] chose instead to focus on the expansion of the existing heavy rail network, including the North West Rail Link and [[South West Rail Link]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman|first1=Peter|title=An end to Sydney's transport lost years?|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-opinion/an-end-to-sydneys-transport-lost-years-20100222-ornm.html|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=23 February 2010|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924180236/http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-opinion/an-end-to-sydneys-transport-lost-years-20100222-ornm.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Revival===
[[File:Sydney Metro logo.svg|thumb|120x120px|left|Project logo]]
In mid-2012, the newly elected [[O'Farrell ministry|Coalition government]] announced [[Proposed railways in Sydney#NSW Transport Masterplan.2C 2012|Sydney's Rail Future]] and the NSW Transport Masterplan.<ref name=srf /> Under this proposal, the North West Rail Link would be built as a single-deck, privately operated metro connecting to a future second harbour crossing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saulwick|first1=Jacob|title=Sydney transport shake-up: plan for single deck metro-style trains and second harbour crossing|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/sydney-transport-shake-up-plan-for-single-deck-metro-style-trains-and-second-harbour-crossing-20120620-20ngm.html |url-access=registration |publisher=Fairfax Media|date=20 June 2012|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=28 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628155546/http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/sydney-transport-shakeup-plan-for-single-deck-metrostyle-trains-and-second-harbour-crossing-20120620-20ngm.html|url-status=live}}</ref> These plans received criticism on the basis that they might not have the capacity of existing double-deck trains<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saulwick|first1=Jacob|title=Secret report casts doubt on train plan|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/secret-report-casts-doubt-on-train-plan-20130922-2u7zg.html |url-access=registration |publisher=Fairfax Media|date=23 September 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=25 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425120748/http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/secret-report-casts-doubt-on-train-plan-20130922-2u7zg.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and concerns over the inability of trains on the existing network to use the new crossing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saulwick|first1=Jacob|title=Tunnel too small could make rail link a bridge too far|url=http://www.drive.com.au/roads-and-traffic/tunnel-too-small-could-make-rail-link-a-bridge-too-far-20120703-21fjy.html|publisher=Fairfax Media|date=4 July 2012|newspaper=Drive |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315221234/http://www.drive.com.au/it-pro/tunnel-too-small-could-make-rail-link-a-bridge-too-far-20120703-21fjy |archive-date=15 March 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Later, the route was extended and the name changed to Sydney Metro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/nsw-tests-the-market-over-sydney-metro-construction/story-e6frg8zx-1227410122521|title=NSW tests the market over Sydney Metro construction|work=[[The Australian]]|date=23 June 2015|access-date=13 July 2015}}</ref>

In 2014, the Government announced the second harbour crossing under the name [[Proposed railways in Sydney#Sydney Metro|Sydney Rapid Transit]], as part of the 'Rebuilding NSW' infrastructure plan funded through the sale of electricity infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transforming Sydney: Sydney Rapid Transit|url=http://www.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/miscellaneous/sydney-rapid-transit_sis2014.pdf|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=November 2014|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=31 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331210536/http://www.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/miscellaneous/sydney-rapid-transit_sis2014.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rebuilding NSW|url=http://www.nsw.gov.au/rebuilding|publisher=NSW Government|access-date=15 June 2015|date=November 2014|archive-date=23 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623032918/http://www.nsw.gov.au/rebuilding|url-status=dead}}</ref> The new railway would cross [[Port Jackson|Sydney Harbour]], tunnel beneath the CBD, and join a converted portion of the [[Bankstown railway line|Bankstown line]] up to [[Bankstown railway station]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Geralthy, Sarah|author2=Liz, Foschia|title=Sydney rapid transit rail build could begin in three years, NSW Transport Minister Gladys Berejiklian says|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-06-11/sydney-rapid-transit-rail-could-begin-gladys-berejiklian/5515186|publisher=ABC News|date=11 June 2014|access-date=11 June 2014|archive-date=12 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140612014454/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-06-11/sydney-rapid-transit-rail-could-begin-gladys-berejiklian/5515186|url-status=live}}</ref>

The system was officially renamed 'Sydney Metro' in June 2015 following the passage of power privatisation bills.<ref>{{cite web|title=Funding secured: Sydney Metro to be a reality|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/funding-secured-sydney-metro-be-reality|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=4 June 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623191517/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/funding-secured-sydney-metro-be-reality|archive-date=23 June 2015}}</ref> Opposing parties warned the government that the sale of the power infrastructure may not provide the capital needed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gerathy|first1=Sarah|title=Power vote means Sydney Harbour rail crossing is less than a decade away: NSW Premier Mike Baird|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-04/new-sydney-harbour-crossing-at-rocket-speed-after-power-vote/6521304|publisher=ABC News|date=4 June 2015|access-date=15 June 2015|archive-date=16 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116111125/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-04/new-sydney-harbour-crossing-at-rocket-speed-after-power-vote/6521304|url-status=live}}</ref>

In July 2018, Sydney Metro was established as a [[statutory body|statutory authority]], tasked with leading the delivery of the metro system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/new-transport-era-sydney-metro-authority-comes-effect|title=New transport era as Sydney Metro authority comes into effect|date=5 July 2018|website=Transport for NSW|access-date=27 May 2019|archive-date=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711152017/https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/new-transport-era-sydney-metro-authority-comes-effect|url-status=live}}</ref> Peter Regan has been the Chief Executive of the agency since March 2021.<ref name="chief" />

In January 2023, it was announced that the emergency exits in tunnels on the Metro West and Metro Western Sydney Airport lines will be spaced at {{convert|240|m|yd|abbr=on}} where possible, matching the existing lines.<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Sullivan |first=Matt |date=25 January 2023 |title=Major backflip on emergency exits for Sydney Metro rail tunnels |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/major-backflip-on-emergency-exits-for-sydney-metro-rail-tunnels-20230125-p5cfd3.html |access-date=25 January 2023 |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |archive-date=25 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230125080444/https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/major-backflip-on-emergency-exits-for-sydney-metro-rail-tunnels-20230125-p5cfd3.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2023, as part of the [[2023 New South Wales state election|2023 state election campaign]], the government of [[Dominic Perrottet]] announced business cases would be produced for further extensions for the Sydney Metro network.<ref name=":2">{{Cite press release |last1= Perrottet |first1= Dominic |author-link1= Dominic Perrottet |last2= Stokes |first2= Rob |author-link2= Rob Stokes |last3= Elliott |first3= David |author-link3= David Elliott (politician) |date= 12 February 2023 |title= Metro boost for Western Sydney |url= https://www.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/metro-boost-for-western-sydney |publisher= [[Government of New South Wales|NSW Government]] |access-date=13 February 2023 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230213091735/https://www.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/metro-boost-for-western-sydney |archive-date=13 February 2023}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Ward |first=Mary |date=11 February 2023 |title=Construction on four new metro lines could begin this year |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/construction-on-four-new-metro-lines-could-begin-this-year-20230211-p5cjqh.html |access-date=13 February 2023 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en |archive-date=13 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230213091733/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/construction-on-four-new-metro-lines-could-begin-this-year-20230211-p5cjqh.html |url-status=live }}</ref> This included the following links:
* Tallawong to St Marys
* Westmead to the Aerotropolis (Bradfield Station)
* Bankstown to Glenfield via Liverpool
* Macarthur to the Aerotropolis (Bradfield Station)<ref name=":2" />

== Operations ==
Sydney Metro services are operated by [[Metro Trains Sydney]], a joint venture between [[MTR Corporation]], [[ComfortDelGro]], and [[UGL Rail]], who will operate and maintain the network under a 15-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourmetro.com.au/about-us/|title=About Us|website=Metro Trains Sydney|access-date=29 May 2019|archive-date=6 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506015655/https://www.ourmetro.com.au/about-us/|url-status=live}}</ref> The network is fully automated to the [[Automatic train operation|GoA4]] level<ref>{{cite web |title=Case Studies: Sydney Metro – Western Sydney Airport Proposal – Australia |url=https://www.northstarconsultancy.com/sydney-metro-western-sydney-airport-australia/ |website=northstarconsultancy.com |access-date=28 January 2024 |archive-date=28 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240128083728/https://www.northstarconsultancy.com/sydney-metro-western-sydney-airport-australia/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and uses [[Communications-based train control|CBTC]] signalling throughout.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pearce |first1=Connor |title=Integrated signalling systems providing reliability on Sydney Metro |url=https://www.railexpress.com.au/integrated-signalling-systems-providing-reliability-on-sydney-metro/ |access-date=28 January 2024 |publisher=Rail Express |date=14 July 2020 |archive-date=28 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240128083728/https://www.railexpress.com.au/integrated-signalling-systems-providing-reliability-on-sydney-metro/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Network===
{{Main|Metro North West & Bankstown Line}}

The [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line]] is currently the only line in the Sydney Metro network, linking [[Tallawong railway station|Tallawong]] to [[Sydenham railway station, Sydney|Sydenham]] with 21 stations along a {{convert|52|km|mi|abbr=on}} distance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themetrorailguy.com/sydney-metro-information-route-map-fare-prices-pass-hours-timings/|title=Sydney Metro – Information, Route Map, Fare & Timings|website=The Metro Rail Guy|language=en-US|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-date=18 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240818222304/https://themetrorailguy.com/metro-rail-systems/sydney-metro-information-route-map-fare-prices-pass-hours-timings/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Services began between Tallawong and [[Chatswood railway station|Chatswood]] in May 2019. For the first 6 months of operation, they were supplemented with trackwork-style rail replacement buses for late-night services from Sundays to Wednesdays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW1-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-20190526.pdf|title=NW1 Timetable – May 2019|website=Transport Info NSW|access-date=10 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505210504/https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW1-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-20190526.pdf|archive-date=5 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW2-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-Limited-Stops-20190526.pdf|title=NW2 Timetable – May 2019|website=Transport Info NSW|access-date=10 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505210704/https://transportnsw.info/documents/timetables/36-NW2-Tallawong-to-Chatswood-Limited-Stops-20190526.pdf|archive-date=5 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The section to [[Sydenham railway station, Sydney|Sydenham]] through the city centre opened in August 2024.<ref name=":4" />

===Capacity===
[[File:Kellyville Station, Sydney, Australia 08.jpg|thumb|[[Platform screen doors]] are standard across the network.]]
The Metro North West & Bankstown Line currently operates with 6-car trains running on 4-minute [[headway]]s. After the addition of the Stage 2 extension to Bankstown, the stations' platforms will be configured to allow for future use of 8-car trains and the signalling system designed to allow for 2-minute headways, both of which are planned to be introduced once increased patronage demands it. Eight-car trains have a design capacity of 1,539 customers and increasing the running frequency to ultimately 30 trains per hour (2-minute headway) would provide a maximum capacity of 46,170 passengers per hour per direction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sydney Metro City & Southwest &#124;page 51 Business Case Summary |url=http://www.sydneymetro.info/sites/default/files/Sydney%20Metro%20CSW%20Business%20Case%20Summary.pdf |access-date=28 February 2017 |publisher=Transport for NSW |archive-date=17 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117015648/http://www.sydneymetro.info/sites/default/files/Sydney%20Metro%20CSW%20Business%20Case%20Summary.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

