==== Metropolis ====
{{main|Sydney Metro Metropolis Stock}}

The network currently operates using 45 6-car [[Sydney Metro Metropolis Stock|Metropolis Stock]] trains, which are fully automated [[electric multiple unit]]s. Each single-deck train features two dedicated areas for prams, luggage and bicycles. There are three doorways per side per carriage and no internal doors between the carriages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.partners.alstom.com/StreamedAsset.axd?assetid=eec46df7-20f4-4ca0-b084-48fd3bab023e&size=Original&disposition=inline|title=Case study: North West Rail Link, Sydney, Australia|publisher=Alstom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304121646/https://assets.partners.alstom.com/StreamedAsset.axd?assetid=eec46df7-20f4-4ca0-b084-48fd3bab023e&size=Original&disposition=inline|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=14 October 2015}}</ref> In a 6-car configuration, the trains have a seating capacity of 378 people, with a total capacity of 1,100.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/sydney-metro-northwest-transport-minister-unveils-life-size-model-of-metropolis-carriage/story-fni0cx12-1227597579623|title=Sydney Metro Northwest: Transport minister unveils life-size model of Metropolis carriage|last1=O'Rourke|first1=Jim|date=5 November 2015|access-date=7 November 2015|website=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Seating arrangements on the Alstom trains are longitudinal, following the style of most other metro trains.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.raillynews.com/2017/alstoms-first-make-india-metro-inaugurated-kochi/|title=Alstom's first 'Make in India' Metro inaugurated in Kochi|date=19 June 2017|work=raillynews.com|access-date=21 January 2018|archive-date=21 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121184502/http://www.raillynews.com/2017/alstoms-first-make-india-metro-inaugurated-kochi/|url-status=live}}</ref> The trains utilise Alstom's trademark Urbalis 400 Grade-of-Automation signalling system that ensures that trains are capable of operating automatically at all times including door closing, obstacle detection and emergencies.

Before the introduction of services, a full-scale model of the new train was built for use on public display, including at the annual [[Sydney Royal Easter Show]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/rouse-hill-times/model-of-sydney-metro-train-will-provide-close-look-how-the-new-rail-link-will-transform-transport-in-nsw/news-story/324631cb383e29904402a89cb82ce488|title=Check out the Sydney Metro train|access-date=29 July 2017|archive-date=2 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210902051351/https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/rouse-hill-times/model-of-sydney-metro-train-will-provide-close-look-how-the-new-rail-link-will-transform-transport-in-nsw/news-story/324631cb383e29904402a89cb82ce488|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proj-x.com.au/news/portfolio-items/transport-nsw-sydney-metro-marquee-sydney-royal-easter-show-2016/|title=Transport for NSW Sydney Metro Marquee at the Sydney Royal Easter Show 2016 - Proj-X Design|website=www.proj-x.com.au|access-date=29 July 2017|archive-date=28 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328033637/https://www.proj-x.com.au/news/portfolio-items/transport-nsw-sydney-metro-marquee-sydney-royal-easter-show-2016/|url-status=dead}}</ref> The trains were built at Alstom's rolling stock manufacturing facility in [[Sri City]], India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themetrorailguy.com/2017/09/28/sydney-metro-receives-first-indian-built-alstom-train/|title=Sydney Metro Receives First Indian Built Alstom Train|date=28 September 2017|website=The Metro Rail Guy|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-date=12 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112021214/https://themetrorailguy.com/2017/09/28/sydney-metro-receives-first-indian-built-alstom-train/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/first-metro-trains-arrive-for-new-83-billion-line-to-sydneys-north-west-20170926-gyost6.html|title=First metro trains arrive for new $8.3 billion line to Sydney's north west|date=26 September 2017|work=Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=20 January 2018|archive-date=21 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121074308/http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/first-metro-trains-arrive-for-new-83-billion-line-to-sydneys-north-west-20170926-gyost6.html|url-status=live}}</ref> with the first six-car Sydney Metro train arriving in Rouse Hill in September 2017 to undergo testing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/first-sydney-metro-train-arrives|title=First Sydney Metro train arrives|date=26 September 2017|work=NSW Government|access-date=27 September 2017|archive-date=12 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210212024437/https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/first-sydney-metro-train-arrives|url-status=live}}</ref>

In February 2018, dynamic testing on the first of the trainsets began.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.metro-report.com/news/single-view/view/sydney-metro-train-on-test.html|title=Sydney metro train on test|last=UK|first=DVV Media|work=Metro Report|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-date=24 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324204002/https://www.metro-report.com/news/single-view/view/sydney-metro-train-on-test.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Testing was done on brakes, passenger information displays, lighting and door operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/first-metro-train-testing|title=First Metro Train Testing|website=www.sydneymetro.info|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-date=31 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731191657/https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/first-metro-train-testing|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2019, an additional 23 6-car sets were ordered<ref>{{Cite web |date=22 November 2019 |title=Alstom to supply driverless trains and digital signalling system for Sydney Metro extension to City and Southwest |url=https://www.alstom.com/press-releases-news/2019/11/alstom-supply-driverless-trains-and-digital-signalling-system-sydney |access-date=4 December 2024 |website=Alstom |language=en}}</ref> for the [[Sydney Metro City & Southwest|City & Southwest]] extension from the existing 22 sets, as of December 2024, all 23 sets have been delivered and are operational on the line. 

==== Inspiro ====
{{main|Sydney Metro Inspiro Stock}}

For the [[Sydney Metro Western Sydney Airport|Western Sydney Airport]], [[Siemens Mobility|Siemens]] will supply 12 3-car [[Siemens Inspiro]] driverless sets. These trains will enter service on the line from 2027, after the opening date of late 2026 was pushed back into 2027.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transform mobility in Western Sydney |url=https://www.mobility.siemens.com/global/en/portfolio/references/sydney-metro-western-sydney-airport.html |website=[[Siemens Mobility]] |access-date=15 September 2024}}</ref>

