==Project history==
===Sydney Metro Northwest===
{{main|Sydney Metro Northwest}}

[[File:SydneyMetro29.jpg|thumb|[[Tallawong railway station|Tallawong station]], the northern terminus of the current [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line|North West & Bankstown Line]]]]
[[File:SydneyMetro17.jpg|thumb|The [[Epping to Chatswood rail link|Epping to Chatswood]] section of the North West Line was originally opened in 2009 as part of the Sydney Trains network and later converted to allow the operation of autonomous trains.]]
Construction of the first section of the [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line]] began in late 2013,<ref>{{cite web |date=23 October 2013 |title=Construction ramps up as Showground Station site is cleared |url=http://nwrail.transport.nsw.gov.au/News/Latest-news/Construction-ramps-up-as-Showground-Station-site-i |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107200612/http://nwrail.transport.nsw.gov.au/News/Latest-news/Construction-ramps-up-as-Showground-Station-site-i |archive-date=7 November 2015 |access-date=7 November 2015 |publisher=Transport for NSW}}</ref> linking [[Tallawong railway station|Tallawong]], in Sydney's north-western suburbs to [[Chatswood railway station|Chatswood]]. The line consists of {{convert|23|km|mi|abbr=on}} of new track between [[Rouse Hill]] and [[Epping railway station, Sydney|Epping]], which includes eight new stations. At Epping, the line connects to the existing {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Epping to Chatswood rail link]], which was separated from the [[Sydney Trains]] network and converted to allow the operation of single-deck autonomous trains with [[platform screen doors]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Green light for the North West Rail Link|url=http://nwrail.transport.nsw.gov.au/NorthWestRailLink/handlers/DownloadMediaFile.ashx?file=~%2FNorthWestRailLink%2Fmedia%2FNWRL%2FOriginal%2Fnewsletter%2F13180-Project-newsletter-update_ALIGNMENT_6pp_LR.pdf%3Fext%3D.pdf|publisher=Transport for NSW|access-date=7 November 2015|date=June 2013|archive-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083845/http://nwrail.transport.nsw.gov.au/NorthWestRailLink/handlers/DownloadMediaFile.ashx?file=~%2FNorthWestRailLink%2Fmedia%2FNWRL%2FOriginal%2Fnewsletter%2F13180-Project-newsletter-update_ALIGNMENT_6pp_LR.pdf%3Fext%3D.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> Passengers can interchange with the existing system at both Epping and Chatswood. The first section of the line opened in May 2019.

In November 2016, Sydney Metro, in particular, the [[John Holland Group]], [[Dragados]] and Transport for NSW, were awarded the 2016 NSW Premier's Award for Building Infrastructure for the {{convert|15|km|mi|abbr=on}} twintunnels in [[Bella Vista, New South Wales|Bella Vista]] and Epping, which are currently the longest tunnels constructed in Australia.<ref name="ExcellenceAward">{{cite news|title=Sydney Metro receives awards for excellence|work=Trenchless Australasia|url=https://www.trenchless-australasia.com/2016/11/28/sydney-metro-receives-awards-excellence/|date=28 November 2016|access-date=28 November 2016|archive-date=28 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128195909/https://www.trenchless-australasia.com/2016/11/28/sydney-metro-receives-awards-excellence/|url-status=live}}</ref> The completion of these tunnels in early 2016 marked the completion of the first stage of Sydney Metro Northwest. The NSW Premier's award recognises "infrastructure projects in the state that make a difference to the local community".<ref name="ExcellenceAward" />

===Sydney Metro City & Southwest===
[[File:Victoria Cross Station Sydney 08.jpg|thumb|Victoria Cross Station on the City and Southwest section of the line]]
{{main|Sydney Metro City & Southwest}}

Construction of the extension of the [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line]] began in mid-2017, extending the line an additional {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} from {{rwsa|Chatswood}} on the [[North Shore (Sydney)|North Shore]], through the [[Sydney central business district|Sydney CBD]] and to [[Sydenham railway station, Sydney|Sydenham]]. The centrepiece of the project is a new twin-tunnel rail crossing under [[Port Jackson|Sydney Harbour]]. This new section of the line opened on 19 August 2024. From Sydenham, a second stage of the extension will convert a section of the existing [[Bankstown railway line]] to rapid-transit standards, further extending the line to a final terminus at [[Bankstown railway station|Bankstown]]. This final extension will open in 2026.<ref name=2026-completion/>

Together with planned improvements to the [[Main Western railway line, New South Wales|Main Western line]], the project is expected to increase capacity on the Sydney rail network by up to 60%, and allow for the movement of over 100,000 extra commuters across the network every hour.<ref name=walker>{{cite web|last1=Walker|first1=Ian|title=Construction begins on second Sydney Harbour rail crossing|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/construction-begins-on-second-sydney-harbour-rail-crossing/story-fni0cx12-1227296245667|website=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=23 April 2015}}</ref> The City & Southwest extension represents the first phase of the "southern sector conversion" envisaged in ''Sydney's Rail Future''.<ref name=srf>{{cite book|title=Sydney's rail future: modernising Sydney's trains|date=June 2012|author=Transport for NSW|author-link=Transport for NSW|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/sydneys-rail-future.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626104616/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/publications/sydneys-rail-future.pdf|archive-date=26 June 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Sydney Metro West===
{{main|Sydney Metro West}}

Sydney Metro West is a separate line between the Sydney CBD and [[Westmead, New South Wales|Westmead]]. The line was announced as an official project in November 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/newsroom/media-releases/sydney-metro-west-new-railway-more-trains-western-sydney |title= Sydney Metro West: a new railway, more trains for Western Sydney |date= 14 November 2016 |publisher= Transport for NSW |access-date= 14 November 2016 |archive-date= 29 April 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170429171125/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/newsroom/media-releases/sydney-metro-west-new-railway-more-trains-western-sydney |url-status= live }}</ref> with up to 12 stations being considered including station locations at [[Parramatta]], [[Sydney Olympic Park]], [[Five Dock]], [[Bays Precinct|the Bays Precinct]] and the CBD. In March 2018, the government announced that an additional station would be built at Westmead, as well as one that connected to either of the existing stations at [[Concord West railway station|Concord West]] or [[North Strathfield railway station|North Strathfield]].<ref name="Sydney Metro 2018-03-23">{{cite web|title=Further Sydney Metro West stations revealed|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/further-sydney-metro-west-stations-revealed|website=Sydney Metro|publisher=Transport for NSW|access-date=23 March 2018|date=23 March 2018|archive-date=23 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323155541/https://www.sydneymetro.info/article/further-sydney-metro-west-stations-revealed|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="SMH 2018-03-23">{{cite news|last1=O'Sullivan|first1=Matt|title=The Sydney suburbs on list of station sites for new metro line|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/the-sydney-suburbs-on-list-of-station-sites-for-new-metro-line-20180323-p4z5vw.html|access-date=23 March 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=23 March 2018|archive-date=23 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323061752/https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/the-sydney-suburbs-on-list-of-station-sites-for-new-metro-line-20180323-p4z5vw.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

The 2019–2020 New South Wales state budget in June 2019 allocated funding of $6.4 billion over four years to the project, with construction to be fast-tracked to start in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/government-getting-it-done-on-metro-west|title=Government getting it done on Metro West|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=18 June 2019|access-date=19 June 2019|archive-date=8 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108214726/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/government-getting-it-done-on-metro-west|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalconstructionreview.com/news/34bn-added-fast-forward-sydney-metro-west/|title=$3.4bn added to fast-forward Sydney metro west|publisher=Global Construction Review (GCR)|date=18 June 2019|access-date=19 June 2019|archive-date=18 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162733/http://www.globalconstructionreview.com/news/34bn-added-fast-forward-sydney-metro-west/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=budget2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.budget.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/budget-2019-06/Budget_Paper_2-Infrastructure%20Statement-Budget_201920.pdf|title=Infrastructure Statement 2019–2020 Budget Paper No.2|website=NSW Government|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-date=19 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619205004/https://www.budget.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/budget-2019-06/Budget_Paper_2-Infrastructure%20Statement-Budget_201920.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

The government announced and confirmed seven station locations along the line in 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/construction-of-western-sydney-metro-to-start-next-year|title=Construction of the Western Sydney Metro to start next year|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=21 October 2019|access-date=21 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021025324/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/construction-of-western-sydney-metro-to-start-next-year|archive-date=21 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="abc-oct2019">{{cite web |date=21 October 2019 |title=NSW Government confirms seven new Sydney train stations for Metro West project |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-10-21/nsw-government-unveils-metro-west-train-stops/11622038 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021083211/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-10-21/nsw-government-unveils-metro-west-train-stops/11622038 |archive-date=21 October 2019 |access-date=21 October 2019 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/sites/default/files/document-library/Sydney_Metro_West_Scoping_Newsletter_October_2019.pdf|title=Sydney Metro West stations confirmed|publisher=NSW Government|website=Sydney Metro|date=21 October 2019|access-date=21 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021025244/https://www.sydneymetro.info/sites/default/files/document-library/Sydney_Metro_West_Scoping_Newsletter_October_2019.pdf|archive-date=21 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> with a further 2 stations announced in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-05-12/nsw-new-metro-stations-for-sydney-cbd-revealed/100133164|title=City buildings to be acquired by NSW government for construction of two new metro rail stations|publisher=ABC News|date=12 May 2021|access-date=12 May 2021|archive-date=12 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210512013727/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-05-12/nsw-new-metro-stations-for-sydney-cbd-revealed/100133164|url-status=live}}</ref> Tunnelling commenced in 2023<ref>{{cite web | last=May | first=Tiana | title=Tunnelling Begins on Sydney Metro West Line | website=Railway-News | date=5 June 2023 | url=https://railway-news.com/tunnelling-begins-on-sydney-metro-west-line/ | access-date=5 December 2025}}</ref> and completed in December 2025.<ref>{{cite web | last=Stoate | first=Joey | title=Sydney Metro West: TBM Dorothy Completes Journey to Westmead | website=Railway-News | date=4 December 2025 | url=https://railway-news.com/sydney-metro-west-tbm-dorothy-completes-journey-to-westmead/ | access-date=5 December 2025}}</ref> The line is expected to completed by 2032.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lock |first=Maeve Bannister and Samantha |date=7 December 2023 |title='Reset' for troubled rail project with late launch date |url=https://www.theleader.com.au/story/8450845/reset-for-troubled-rail-project-with-late-launch-date/ |access-date=25 January 2024 |website=St George & Sutherland Shire Leader |language=en-AU |archive-date=25 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240125055405/https://www.theleader.com.au/story/8450845/reset-for-troubled-rail-project-with-late-launch-date/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Sydney Metro Western Sydney Airport ===
{{Main|Sydney Metro Western Sydney Airport}}

In March 2018, the federal and state governments signed the Western Sydney City Deal and announced the development of stage 1 of the North-South Link as part of the deal.<ref name="city deal march 2018">{{cite web|title=Western Sydney City Deal to deliver rail, investment and jobs|url=https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/western-sydney-city-deal-to-deliver-rail-investment-and-jobs|date=4 March 2018|publisher=Transport for NSW|access-date=6 March 2018|archive-date=6 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306142452/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/western-sydney-city-deal-to-deliver-rail-investment-and-jobs|url-status=live}}</ref> Stage 1 of the Western Sydney Airport line will operate between [[St Marys railway station, Sydney|St Marys]] and Badgerys Creek [[Aerotropolis]] via [[Western Sydney Airport]]. Construction commenced in late 2020 and was planned to be complete to coincide with the opening of the new airport in 2026<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney City Deal –Connectivity|url=https://cities.infrastructure.gov.au/22446/documents/72484|publisher=Department of Infrastructure, Regional Development and Cities|access-date=16 March 2018|archive-date=16 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214108/https://cities.infrastructure.gov.au/22446/documents/72484|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/politics/west-syd-airport-metro-line-expedited-c-1071166|title=Scott Morrison announces construction on Western Sydney Airport metro line to start this year|publisher=7News|date=1 June 2020|access-date=1 June 2020|archive-date=9 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200609093515/https://7news.com.au/politics/west-syd-airport-metro-line-expedited-c-1071166|url-status=live}}</ref> however, it is now anticipated that the new line will not be ready until April 2027.<ref>{{cite web | last=O'Sullivan | first=Matt | title=Sydney Metro: St Marys-Bradfield line to open late | website=The Sydney Morning Herald | date=13 February 2025 | url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/late-opening-for-11-billion-metro-line-to-sydney-s-new-international-airport-20250211-p5lb7o.html | access-date=24 February 2025}}</ref>

In the 2019–2020 federal budget in April 2019, the federal government announced a contribution of $3.5 billion to deliver stage 1 of the rail link.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney North South Rail Link Package|url=https://investment.infrastructure.gov.au/key_projects/road_and_rail_delivery/western_sydney_north_south_rail_link.aspx|website=Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Cities and Regional Development|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-date=24 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924035023/https://investment.infrastructure.gov.au/key_projects/road_and_rail_delivery/western_sydney_north_south_rail_link.aspx|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Federal Budget 2019: Western Sydney Airport rail line, North–South Rail Link included in NSW $7.3b infrastructure boost|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/the-economy/federal-budget-2019-nsw-gets-73b-infrastructure-boost-20190328-h1cwsl.html|date=2 April 2019|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-date=3 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703154331/https://www.smh.com.au/business/the-economy/federal-budget-2019-nsw-gets-73b-infrastructure-boost-20190328-h1cwsl.html|url-status=live}}</ref> This funding includes $50 million towards the business case process for the North-South Rail Link and $61 million for the Elizabeth Drive overpass. In the 2019–2020 New South Wales state budget in June 2019, the state government announced an investment of $2.0 billion to begin the construction of stage 1 for the next 4 years.<ref name="budget20192">{{cite web|title=Infrastructure Statement 2019–2020 Budget Paper No.2|url=https://www.budget.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/budget-2019-06/Budget_Paper_2-Infrastructure%20Statement-Budget_201920.pdf|website=NSW Government|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-date=19 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619205004/https://www.budget.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/budget-2019-06/Budget_Paper_2-Infrastructure%20Statement-Budget_201920.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

This line will utilise a much higher [[25 kV AC railway electrification|voltage]] than that of the North West, City & Southwest lines, this time a single-phase alternating current at 25 kV 50&nbsp;Hz. This means that the line will not be interoperable with the existing Sydney Metro or Sydney Trains network. This line will operate with a different class of rolling stock, manufactured by [[Siemens Mobility]].<ref name="wsa" />

==Potential extensions==
===Western Sydney===
The [[Metro North West & Bankstown Line|North West line]] is proposed to be extended to [[St Marys railway station, Sydney|St Marys]] to the west via [[Schofields railway station|Schofields]], connecting to the [[Sydney Metro Western Sydney Airport|Western Sydney Airport line]] and [[North Shore & Western Line|North Shore & Western]] lines.<ref name=":2" /> Previous plans have shown connections between the North West & Bankstown Line and Western Sydney Airport Line potentially occurring at either Schofields, extending both lines, or [[Tallawong railway station|Tallawong]], through extension of the Western Sydney Airport line. It will not be possible for the two lines to be connected as a single line due to incompatible train lengths and power systems; 1500V DC vs 25kV AC.

The Western Sydney Airport line is planned to be extended to the [[Airport & South Line]] at [[Macarthur railway station|Macarthur]] and [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield]] to the south.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title=Sydney Metro Corporate Plan|url=https://www.sydneymetro.info/sites/default/files/document-library/Sydney_Metro_Corporate_Plan.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112024600/https://www.sydneymetro.info/sites/default/files/document-library/Sydney_Metro_Corporate_Plan_2019-2021_June20.pdf |archive-date=12 November 2020 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=":2" />

The [[Sydney Metro West|West]] line would be extended from [[Westmead railway station|Westmead]] to the [[Bradfield railway station, Sydney|Bradfield Station]]<ref name=":2" /> or [[Western Sydney Airport]].<ref name=":1" />

===South Western Sydney===
The City & Southwest line is being planned to be extended from [[Bankstown railway station|Bankstown]] to [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield]]<ref name=":2" /> via [[Liverpool railway station, Sydney|Liverpool]],<ref name=":1" /> with a further potential extension to [[Bradfield railway station, Sydney|Bradfield Station]] via the existing [[South West Rail Link|South West Rail link]] that serves [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]].<ref name=":3" /> The second phase of the southern sector conversion would see two of the four tracks between [[Sydenham railway station, Sydney|Sydenham]] and [[Hurstville railway station|Hurstville]], part of the Sydney Trains [[South Coast railway line, New South Wales|Illawarra line]], converted to form part of the Sydney Metro network. This would increase rail capacity between Hurstville and the city by 10 trains per hour. Though a precise construction timeframe was not provided, the plan envisages all work being completed by 2031. The Hurstville conversion would add eight stations and {{convert|9|km|abbr=on}} to the metro network.<ref name="srf" /> Developing plans for this extension has proven difficult, and ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' reported in February 2016 that the project may have been dropped.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Sullivan|first1=Matt|last2=Saulwick|first2=Jacob|date=3 February 2016|title=Plan to extend Sydney metro line south hits growing list of hurdles|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/plan-to-extend-sydney-metro-line-south-hits-growing-list-of-hurdles-20160201-gmj9dz.html|access-date=4 September 2016|archive-date=15 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115172218/http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/plan-to-extend-sydney-metro-line-south-hits-growing-list-of-hurdles-20160201-gmj9dz.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===South Eastern Sydney===
The South East Sydney Transport Strategy of the New South Wales government envisions a metro line starting from the CBD with stations at [[Green Square, New South Wales|Green Square]], [[Randwick]], two at [[Maroubra, New South Wales|Maroubra]], [[Malabar, New South Wales|Malabar]] and [[La Perouse, New South Wales|La Perouse]] built by 2041, as well as another one from Randwick to [[Eastlakes, New South Wales|Eastlakes]] and, via the Domestic and International terminals of [[Sydney Airport]], further on to [[Brighton-Le-Sands, New South Wales|Brighton-Le-Sands]] and then [[Kogarah, New South Wales|Kogarah]] by 2056.<ref>{{Cite web|title=South East Sydney Transport Strategy|url=https://future.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/media/documents/2020/SES_Transport_Strategy.pdf|access-date=5 September 2020|archive-date=1 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101064632/https://future.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/media/documents/2020/SES_Transport_Strategy.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

